{{DEFAULTSORT:さんしゆうはんしん}} [[Category:神仏習合]] [[Category:法華系仏教]] [[Category:日本の神]] [[Category:護法神]] [[Category:名数30|はんしん]] {{shinto-stub}}

'''Sanjuban Shin''' (三十番神) is a term for the 30 deities venerated in the {{ill|english|de|german|ja|神仏習合}} belief, who were thought to protect the nation and its people on a rotating daily basis. The Sanjuban Shin take turns guarding the days of the month, with 30 days per month (since, in the old lunisolar calendar {{ill|english|de|german|ja|太陰太陽暦}}, a month had either 29 or 30 days).

It is said that the first enshrinement was performed by the founder of {{ill|english|de|german|ja|天台宗}}, {{ill|english|de|german|ja|最澄}} (the Great Teacher of Transmission), who enshrined them at {{ill|english|de|german|ja|比叡山}}; they became widely venerated during the Kamakura period. From the medieval period onward, they were particularly esteemed in {{ill|english|de|german|ja|日蓮宗}} and {{ill|english|de|german|ja|法華宗}} ({{ill|english|de|german|ja|法華神道}}), and came to be regarded as deities guarding the {{ill|english|de|german|ja|法華経}} (specifically, as {{ill|english|de|german|ja|護法善神|lt=english|lt_ja=諸天善神|lt_de=german}}). This occurred because {{ill|english|de|german|ja|日像}}, who aimed to propagate Nichiren Buddhism in Kyoto, incorporated the Sanjuban Shin of Mount Hiei for missionary purposes. Furthermore, {{ill|english|de|german|ja|吉田神道}} promoted a different set of Sanjuban Shin, such as the "Heaven and Earth Protection Sanjuban Shin", "Royal City Protection Sanjuban Shin", and "Nation Protection Sanjuban Shin". {{ill|english|de|german|ja|吉田兼倶}} claimed that the belief in the Sanjuban Shin originated from {{ill|english|de|german|ja|吉田神道}}. In {{ill|english|de|german|ja|吉田神道}}, there is also an account that associates them with the "Thirty-Two Deities" of {{ill|english|de|german|ja|天孫降臨}}.<ref>{{Cite journal|和書|author=宮川了篤 |url=https://doi.org/10.15054/00000290 |title=平成二十二年一月二十七日 最終講義 日蓮宗修法史概説 (宮川了篤先生退職記念号) |journal=身延論叢 |publisher=身延山大学仏教学会 |year=2011 |issue=16 |pages=15-16 |ISSN=1342-2715 |doi=10.15054/00000290}}</ref><ref>『[https://dl.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/1224160/26 国民思想叢書. 神道篇]』　加藤咄堂 編　国民思想叢書刊行会 「神道大意」p.23-24（国立国会図書館）</ref>

In 1868, with the separation of Shinto and Buddhism {{ill|english|de|german|ja|神仏分離}}, there was a period in the early Meiji era during which enshrinement was temporarily prohibited (although presently, each sect and temple enshrines them freely in forms such as main hall altars or subsidiary shrines, according to their own discretion).

Historically, there are said to be approximately ten types of Sanjuban Shin: the Guardians of Heaven and Earth, the Guardians of the Inner Palace, the Guardians of the Royal City, the Guardians of Our Nation, the Guardians of the Forbidden Palace, the Guardians of the Lotus Sutra, the Guardians in Accordance with the Dharma, the Guardians of the Lotus Sutra (Scripture), the Guardians of the Nio Sutra, and the Guardians of the Dharma Sutra.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|和書 |title=日本の神々神徳・由来事典 : 神話と信仰にみる神祇・垂迹の姿 (わたしの家の宗教事典選書) |date=2008-03-25 |publisher={{ill|english|de|german|ja|学習研究社|lt=english|lt_ja=Gakken|lt_de=german}} |page=224 |author=三橋 健 |isbn=978-4-05-403651-2}}</ref>

The table below lists the Sanjuban Shin as recognized in Nichiren Buddhism.<ref>[http://gyokurenzan.shinjoji.nichiren-shu.jp/introduction/sanjuban.htm 玉蓮山真成寺 (Uozu, Toyama Prefecture) Website]<br/>[https://ryugesengyo.hatenablog.com/entry/2014/07/24/135153 List of Enshrined Deities at the Sanjuban Hall of Fukakusa-dera (Fushimi, Kyoto)]</ref> Moreover, works such as ‘{{ill|english|de|german|ja|神道大意}}’ and ‘{{ill|english|de|german|ja|拾芥抄}}’ also enumerate the same Sanjuban Shin.

