The Sanjūban-shin were established on the premise of a state safeguarded by Buddhist teachings as recorded in various scriptures – foremost among them the {{ill|Lotus Sutra|de:Lotus-Sutra|german:Lotus-Sutra|ja:法華経}}, as well as texts such as the Vajra Transmission Sutra and {{ill|Nio Sutra|de:Nio-Sutra|german:Nio-Sutra|ja:仁王経|lt=Nio Prajñāpāramitā Sutra|lt_ja=仁王般若波羅蜜経|lt_de=Nio-Prajñāpāramitā-Sutra}}. In the course of the development of Shinto-Buddhism syncretism, these deities were incorporated from the native Japanese pantheon.

In the modern era, because the adoption of the {{ill|Gregorian Calendar|de:Gregorianischer Kalender|german:Gregorianischer Kalender|ja:グレゴリオ暦|lt=Solar Calendar|lt_ja=太陽暦|lt_de:Sonnenkalender}} results in a 31st day each month, on the 31st day some traditions invoke a group known as the Five Benevolent Deities – namely {{ill|Yakushi Bodhisattva|de:Yakushi-Bodhisattva|german:Yakushi-Bodhisattva|ja:薬王菩薩}}, Yūshi Bodhisattva, {{ill|Tamonten|de:Tamonten|german:Tamonten|ja:多聞天}}, {{ill|Jikokuten|de:Jikokuten|german:Jikokuten|ja:持国天}}, {{ill|Kishimojin|de:Kishimojin|german:Kishimojin|ja:鬼子母神}}, and {{ill|Ten Rakshasa Women|de:Zehn Rakshasa-Frauen|german:Zehn Rakshasa-Frauen|ja:十羅刹女}}.<ref>[http://www.hokkeshu.com/event/dic_sa_30.html 法華宗(陣門流)｜三十番神、三十一日はどうなるの]</ref>

