[[ja|三十番神]]
[[de|Dreißig Schutzgötter]]
[[sn|Sanju Banshin]]
[[ja|%E4%B8%89%E5%8D%81%E7%95%AA%E7%A5%9E]]

'''Sanjūban-shin''' (三十番神) are a group of thirty deities of the Shinto-Buddhism syncretic faith who were believed to protect the state and its people on a daily rotating basis. The Sanjūban-shin guard the thirty days of a month (since the old lunisolar calendar, {{ill|Lunisolar Calendar|de|lunisolarer Kalender|de|lunisolarer Kalender|ja|太陰太陽暦|1=Lunisolar calendar|2=ja|3=太陰太陽暦|comment=note that this is not the Japanese lunisolar calendar it is any lunisolar calendar|4=ru|5=Лунно-солнечный календарь|6=de|7=Lunisolarkalender|8=es|9=Calendario lunisolar|10=fr|11=Calendrier luni-solaire|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, had either 29 or 30 days) in rotation.

It is said that the founder of {{ill|Tendai Buddhism|de|Tendai-Buddhismus|de|Tendai-Buddhismus|ja|天台宗|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Saichō|de|Saichō|de|Saichō|ja|最澄|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (posthumously honored as Dengyō Daishi), enshrined them on {{ill|Mount Hiei|de|Berg Hiei|de|Berg Hiei|ja|比叡山|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – this being the origin of their veneration. Their worship flourished during the Kamakura period. From the medieval era onward they were especially emphasized within {{ill|Nichiren Buddhism|de|Nichiren-Buddhismus|de|Nichiren-Buddhismus|ja|日蓮宗|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Hokke Buddhism|de|Hokke-Buddhismus|de|Hokke-Buddhismus|ja|法華宗|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (in the context of {{ill|Hokke Shintō|de|Hokke Shintō|de|Hokke Shintō|ja|法華神道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), being regarded as deities safeguarding the {{ill|Lotus Sutra|de|Lotus-Sutra|de|Lotus-Sutra|ja|法華経|qq=draft|qq=draft}} – specifically as {{ill|Dharma Guardian Deities|de|Dharma-Wächtergötter|de|Dharma-Wächtergötter|ja|護法善神|lt=Various Benevolent Deities|lt_ja=諸天善神|lt_de=Verschiedene Wohlwollende Götter|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. This incorporation was undertaken by {{ill|Nisshō|de|Nisshō|de|Nisshō|ja|日像|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who, in his efforts to propagate Nichiren Buddhism in Kyoto, introduced the Mount Hiei Sanjūban-shin into his missionary work. In addition, {{ill|Yoshida Shintō|de|Yoshida Shintō|de|Yoshida Shintō|ja|吉田神道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} presented an alternative grouping of Sanjūban-shin – proclaiming, for instance, the “Guardians of Heaven and Earth,” “Guardians of the Royal Castle,” and “Guardians of the Nation.” {{ill|Yoshida Kanku|de|Yoshida Kanku|de|Yoshida Kanku|ja|吉田兼倶|qq=draft|qq=draft}} argued that the Sanjūban-shin worship originated from Yoshida Shintō. In Yoshida Shintō there are also accounts linking them with the “Thirty‐two Deities” from the time of the {{ill|Descent of the Heavenly Grandson|de|Himmelsabstieg|de|Himmelsabstieg|ja|天孫降臨|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite journal|和書|author=宮川了篤 |url=https|//doi.org/10.15054/00000290 |title=平成二十二年一月二十七日 最終講義 日蓮宗修法史概説 (宮川了篤先生退職記念号) |journal=身延論叢 |publisher=身延山大学仏教学会 |year=2011 |issue=16 |pages=15-16 |ISSN=1342-2715 |doi=10.15054/00000290}}</ref><ref> 『[https|//dl.ndl.go.jp/info|ndljp/pid/1224160/26 国民思想叢書. 神道篇]』　加藤咄堂 編　国民思想叢書刊行会 「神道大意」p.23-24（国立国会図書館）</ref> In 1868, with the advent of {{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|de|Shinbutsu Bunri|de|Trennung von Shinto und Buddhismus|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the enshrinement of these deities was temporarily prohibited in the early Meiji period (although they are now freely enshrined in various forms – such as in inner sanctuary altars or subsidiary shrines – at the discretion of individual sects and temples).

There are traditionally considered to be about ten different types of Sanjūban-shin, namely the Guardians of Heaven and Earth, Guardians of the Palace, Guardians of the Royal Castle, Guardians of the Nation, Guardians of the Imperial Court, Guardians of the Lotus, Guardians of the True Law, Guardians of the Lotus Sutra, Guardians of the Nio Sutra, and Guardians of the Sutra of the Law.<ref name="|0">{{Cite book|和書 |title=日本の神々神徳・由来事典 | 神話と信仰にみる神祇・垂迹の姿 (わたしの家の宗教事典選書) |date=2008-03-25 |publisher={{ill|Gakken|de|Gakken|de|Gakken|ja|学習研究社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} |page=224 |author=三橋 健 |isbn=978-4-05-403651-2}}</ref>

The following table lists the Sanjūban-shin as recognized in Nichiren Buddhism|<ref>[http|//gyokurenzan.shinjoji.nichiren-shu.jp/introduction/sanjuban.htm {{ill|Atsuta Shrine|de|Atsuta-Schrein|de|Atsuta-Schrein|ja|玉蓮山真成寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Toyama Prefecture, Uozu City) Web site]<br/>[https|//ryugesengyo.hatenablog.com/entry/2014/07/24/135153 List of Enshrined Deities at the Sanjūban-shin Hall of {{ill|Fukakusa Shrine|de|Fukakusa-Schrein|de|Fukakusa-Schrein|ja|深草山宝塔寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Fushimi Ward, Kyoto)]</ref> Furthermore, works such as {{ill|Shintō Taii|de|Shintō Taii|de|Shintō Taii|ja|神道大意|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Shūkaishō|de|Shūkaishō|de|Shūkaishō|ja|拾芥抄|qq=draft|qq=draft}} also list the same thirty deities.<ref>『[https|//dl.ndl.go.jp/info|ndljp/pid/1913348/76 {{ill|Shintō Daijiten, Vol.2|de|Shintō-Daijiten|de|Shintō-Daijiten|ja|神道大辞典|qq=draft|qq=draft}}]』 平凡社 p.125-126（国立国会図書館）</ref>

