The Sanjūban-shin were established on the premise of a state safeguarded by Buddhist teachings as recorded in various scriptures – foremost among them the {{ill|Lotus Sutra|de|Lotus-Sutra|de|Lotus-Sutra|ja|法華経|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lotus Sutra|qq=}}, as well as texts such as the Vajra Transmission Sutra and {{ill|Nio Sutra|de|Nio-Sutra|de|Nio-Sutra|ja|仁王経|lt=Nio Prajñāpāramitā Sutra|lt_ja=仁王般若波羅蜜経|lt_de=Nio-Prajñāpāramitā-Sutra|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nio Sutra|qq=}}. In the course of the development of Shinto-Buddhism syncretism, these deities were incorporated from the native Japanese pantheon.

In the modern era, because the adoption of the {{ill|Gregorian Calendar|1=Gregorian calendar|2=ja|3=グレゴリオ暦|4=fr|5=Calendrier grégorien|6=de|7=Gregorianischer Kalender|8=tl|9=Kalendaryong Gregoryano|10=ru|11=Григорианский календарь|de|Gregorianischer Kalender|de|Gregorianischer Kalender|ja|グレゴリオ暦|lt=Solar Calendar|lt_ja=太陽暦|lt_de|Sonnenkalender|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gregorian Calendar|13=User:Immanuelle/Gregorian calendar|qq=}} results in a 31st day each month, on the 31st day some traditions invoke a group known as the Five Benevolent Deities – namely {{ill|Yakushi Bodhisattva|de|Yakushi-Bodhisattva|de|Yakushi-Bodhisattva|ja|薬王菩薩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yakushi Bodhisattva|qq=}}, Yūshi Bodhisattva, {{ill|Tamonten|de|Tamonten|de|Tamonten|ja|多聞天|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamonten|qq=}}, {{ill|Jikokuten|de|Jikokuten|de|Jikokuten|ja|持国天|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jikokuten|qq=}}, {{ill|Kishimojin|de|Kishimojin|de|Kishimojin|ja|鬼子母神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishimojin|qq=}}, and {{ill|Ten Rakshasa Women|de|Zehn Rakshasa-Frauen|de|Zehn Rakshasa-Frauen|ja|十羅刹女|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ten Rakshasa Women|qq=}}.<ref>[http|//www.hokkeshu.com/event/dic_sa_30.html 法華宗(陣門流)｜三十番神、三十一日はどうなるの]</ref>

