The Sanjūban-shin were established on the premise of a state safeguarded by Buddhist teachings as recorded in various scriptures – foremost among them the {{ill|Lotus Sutra|en|Lotus Sutra|WD=Q861212|lt=Lotus Sutra|1=Lotus Sutra}}, as well as texts such as the Vajra Transmission Sutra and {{ill|Humane King Sutra|en|Humane King Sutra|WD=Q5939265|lt=Nio Prajñāpāramitā Sutra|1=Humane King Sutra}}. In the course of the development of Shinto-Buddhism syncretism, these deities were incorporated from the native Japanese pantheon.

In the modern era, because the adoption of the {{ill|Gregorian calendar|en|Gregorian calendar|WD=Q12138|lt=Solar Calendar|1=Gregorian calendar}} results in a 31st day each month, on the 31st day some traditions invoke a group known as the Five Benevolent Deities – namely {{ill|Bhaiṣajyarāja|en|Bhaiṣajyarāja|WD=Q4900820|lt=Yakushi Bodhisattva|1=Bhaiṣajyarāja}}, Yūshi Bodhisattva, {{ill|Tamonten|de|Tamonten|de|Tamonten|ja|多聞天|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tamonten|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 毘沙門天|1=Vaiśravaṇa|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q866315}}, {{ill|Dhṛtarāṣṭra|en|Dhṛtarāṣṭra|WD=Q1188767|lt=Jikokuten|1=Dhṛtarāṣṭra}}, {{ill|Hariti|en|Hariti|WD=Q1353280|lt=Kishimojin|1=Hariti}}, and {{ill|Ten Rākṣasīs|en|Ten Rākṣasīs|WD=Q11405165|lt=Ten Rakshasa Women|1=Ten Rākṣasīs}}.<ref>[http|//www.hokkeshu.com/event/dic_sa_30.html 法華宗(陣門流)｜三十番神、三十一日はどうなるの]</ref>

